00:15:01,624 --> 00:15:06,004
He's married and his wife's in and out
of institutions. She's schizophrenic.

228
00:15:06,130 --> 00:15:09,092
Sometimes she's terrific,
and then she just breaks down.

229
00:15:09,217 --> 00:15:14,265
He has a sweet daughter. When she goes
to college, he's gonna split permanently.

230
00:15:14,390 --> 00:15:17,937
He's paid his dues, but she helped
him through architectural school.

231
00:15:18,062 --> 00:15:20,231
You found all this out on one date?

232
00:15:20,356 --> 00:15:23,861
I figured he's dying to open up. It's so sad.

233
00:15:23,986 --> 00:15:26,990
Now, what should I wear to my audition?

234
00:15:27,115 --> 00:15:31,204
I've got a singing audition for a Broadway
musical. Of course, I'll never get it.

235
00:15:31,329 --> 00:15:33,165
- Singing?
- Can you believe it?

236
00:15:33,290 --> 00:15:36,460
- Really?
- Well, I mean, why not, you know?

237
00:15:36,586 --> 00:15:42,343
- What have I got to lose?
- I know, I just... I didn't know you sang.

238
00:15:43,219 --> 00:15:45,722
You think everybody in
musicals sings so well?

239
00:15:45,848 --> 00:15:47,642
No, no.

240
00:15:47,767 --> 00:15:49,728
Just that... they sing.

241
00:15:49,853 --> 00:15:51,897
Well, you know...

242
00:15:53,274 --> 00:15:57,488
- I sing a little. I mean...
- Oh, I know. No, I know.

243
00:15:58,698 --> 00:16:01,493
Don't say that, cos confidence
is not my strong point.

244
00:16:01,618 --> 00:16:04,205
No, I'm sorry. I didn't mean that.

245
00:16:04,330 --> 00:16:06,374
I think I can fake my way through a song.

246
00:16:06,499 --> 00:16:08,544
- Uh-huh?
- Easily.

247
00:16:10,755 --> 00:16:15,469
- Why? You don't think it's realistic?
- No, I didn't... That's... No.

248
00:16:15,594 --> 00:16:20,267
I just hate to see you put yourself
in a position where you get hurt.

249
00:16:20,392 --> 00:16:22,770
You know how you take
every single rejection

250
00:16:22,895 --> 00:16:26,317
as a confirmation that you
have no talent or something.

251
00:16:26,442 --> 00:16:29,362
- Yeah, well, maybe I'll get it.
- I hope.

252
00:16:29,487 --> 00:16:32,575
Boy, you really know
how to cut me down.

253
00:16:32,700 --> 00:16:35,662
What? No, don't be so sensitive.
Can't I say anything?

254
00:16:35,787 --> 00:16:39,417
Well, I sing! For Christ's sake,
Hannah, you heard me sing!

255
00:16:39,542 --> 00:16:42,212
OK! What happened?

256
00:16:42,337 --> 00:16:47,678
We were having a really nice time, and
suddenly everything went to bad feeling.

257
00:16:47,803 --> 00:16:50,556
Nobody but you can do that to me.
I don't know why.

258
00:16:50,681 --> 00:16:53,435
Look, everything's going your way.

259
00:16:54,561 --> 00:16:57,232
You're right. I'm happy!

260
00:16:59,151 --> 00:17:03,448
Why must I let my insecurities
spoil everything?

261
00:17:03,907 --> 00:17:07,328
# (Holly) This year's fancies

262
00:17:07,495 --> 00:17:11,041
# Are passing fancies

263
00:17:11,208 --> 00:17:13,252
# But sighing sighs

264
00:17:13,377 --> 00:17:15,338
# Holding hands

265
00:17:15,463 --> 00:17:17,341
# This my heart

266
00:17:17,466 --> 00:17:19,677
# Understands

267
00:17:20,386 --> 00:17:23,682
# I'm old-fashioned

268
00:17:23,808 --> 00:17:27,604
# And I don't mind it

269
00:17:27,729 --> 00:17:31,776
# It's how I want to be

270
00:17:31,901 --> 00:17:36,073
# As long as you'll agree

271
00:17:36,950 --> 00:17:42,749
# To stay old-fashioned

272
00:17:42,874 --> 00:17:46,837
# With me

273
00:17:46,962 --> 00:17:48,631
- Thank you very much.
- Thank you.

274
00:17:48,756 --> 00:17:51,260
- It was very nice.
- Terrific.

275
00:17:51,385 --> 00:17:53,179
April Knox?

276
00:18:00,146 --> 00:18:02,649
# Someday

277
00:18:03,150 --> 00:18:05,820
# When I'm awfully low

278
00:18:06,321 --> 00:18:09,158
# When the world is cold

279
00:18:09,742 --> 00:18:11,661
# I will get a glow

280
00:18:11,786 --> 00:18:15,625
# Just thinking of you

281
00:18:16,375 --> 00:18:21,883
# And the way you look tonight

282
00:18:23,468 --> 00:18:26,180
(Holly) You sounded great.
You may be surprised.

283
00:18:26,305 --> 00:18:29,726
(April) I'm glad we have a catering job
this week. I'm low on money.

284
00:18:29,851 --> 00:18:33,690
Yeah, we have Mr Morris Levine's
80th birthday on Riverside Drive,

285
00:18:33,815 --> 00:18:37,236
or Riverside Memorial Chapel,
depending on his health.

286
00:18:37,361 --> 00:18:39,697
Oh, listen. David called me up.

287
00:18:39,822 --> 00:18:40,991
What?

288
00:18:41,116 --> 00:18:45,413
David called me last night.
He wants to take me to the opera.

289
00:18:45,538 --> 00:18:48,626
- I didn't know what to say.
- You're joking.

290
00:18:48,751 --> 00:18:50,962
No, he called late last night.

291
00:18:52,297 --> 00:18:55,009
I, uh... I'm very surprised.

292
00:18:55,134 --> 00:18:57,887
He wanted to take me to see Rigoletto.

293
00:18:58,013 --> 00:19:01,017
- And you're going?
- Well, I didn't know what to say.

294
00:19:01,142 --> 00:19:03,186
First I said no, but then he pressed it.

295
00:19:03,353 --> 00:19:07,650
He said he'd taken you once
and he really wanted to invite me.

296
00:19:09,402 --> 00:19:11,864
- But I'm seeing him.
- I know, I said that.

297
00:19:12,031 --> 00:19:16,245
But he said it was something
he really felt like doing.

298
00:19:16,411 --> 00:19:18,372
Gee, um...

299
00:19:18,539 --> 00:19:21,168
I don't know what to say.

300
00:19:22,044 --> 00:19:26,591
It's just an evening at the opera.
Did I do wrong in accepting?

301
00:19:27,551 --> 00:19:29,387
Huh?

302
00:19:34,643 --> 00:19:37,981
Why do you think that you would
like to convert to Catholicism?

303
00:19:38,106 --> 00:19:42,570
Well, because I've gotta have something
to believe in, or life is meaningless.

304
00:19:42,695 --> 00:19:48,244
I understand, but why did you make the
decision to choose the Catholic faith?

305
00:19:48,369 --> 00:19:51,290
First of all because it's
a very beautiful religion

306
00:19:51,415 --> 00:19:54,294
and it's a strong religion.
It's very well structured.

307
00:19:54,419 --> 00:19:58,925
I mean the against-school-prayer,
pro-abortion, anti-nuclear wing.

308
00:19:59,050 --> 00:20:01,136
So at the moment
you don't believe in God?

309
00:20:01,261 --> 00:20:06,434
No, and I want to. I'm willing to do
anything. I'll dye Easter eggs, if it works.

310
00:20:06,560 --> 00:20:09,146
I need some evidence.
I gotta have some proof.

311
00:20:09,271 --> 00:20:12,943
If I can't believe in God,
then I don't think life is worth living.

312
00:20:13,068 --> 00:20:17,282
- It means making a very big leap.
- Yes, well, can you help me?

313
00:20:17,407 --> 00:20:20,077
(wailing) Why? Oh, my God!

314
00:20:20,202 --> 00:20:23,123
I don't understand.
I thought you'd be happy.

315
00:20:23,248 --> 00:20:26,252
- How can we be happy?
- Because I never thought of God before.

316
00:20:26,377 --> 00:20:30,090
- Now I'm giving it some thought.
- Catholicism? Why not your own people?

317
00:20:30,215 --> 00:20:35,388
Because I got off to a wrong foot with
my own thing. I need a dramatic change.

318
00:20:35,514 --> 00:20:39,477
- You're gonna believe in Jesus Christ?
- I know it sounds funny, but I'll try.

319
00:20:39,602 --> 00:20:42,982
- But why? We raised you as a Jew.
- Just cos I was born that way...

320
00:20:43,107 --> 00:20:46,319
- I'm old enough to make decisions.
- But why Jesus Christ?

321
00:20:46,444 --> 00:20:50,700
- Why shouldn't you become a Buddhist?
- That's totally alien to me.

322
00:20:50,825 --> 00:20:52,953
You're old. Aren't you afraid of dying?

323
00:20:53,078 --> 00:20:55,623
- Why should I be afraid?
- Cos you won't exist.

324
00:20:55,790 --> 00:20:57,709
- So?
- That doesn't terrify you?

325
00:20:57,834 --> 00:21:00,963
Who thinks about such nonsense?
When I'm dead, I'll be dead.

326
00:21:01,088 --> 00:21:04,259
- But aren't you frightened?
- Of what? I'll be unconscious.

327
00:21:04,384 --> 00:21:06,429
I know, but never to exist again?

328
00:21:06,595 --> 00:21:09,266
- How do you know?
- It doesn't look promising.

329
00:21:09,432 --> 00:21:13,479
Who knows what I'll be?
I'll either be unconscious or I won't.

330
00:21:13,605 --> 00:21:17,067
If not, I'll deal with it then.
I'm not gonna worry now.

331
00:21:17,234 --> 00:21:18,694
Mom, come out!

332
00:21:18,861 --> 00:21:23,117
(mother) Of course there's a God,
you idiot! You don't believe in God?

333
00:21:23,284 --> 00:21:26,037
If there's a God, why is there
so much evil in the world?

334
00:21:26,204 --> 00:21:28,958
On a simplistic level,
why were there Nazis?

335
00:21:29,083 --> 00:21:32,212
- Tell him, Max.
- How the hell do I know?

336
00:21:32,337 --> 00:21:34,840
I don't know how the can opener works.

337
00:21:34,965 --> 00:21:38,053
(# choir singing Latin hymn)

338
00:22:57,572 --> 00:23:00,409
- Hi.
- Hi. Where's Holly?

339
00:23:00,534 --> 00:23:03,872
She's auditioning for a TV commercial.
She said she'd be late.

340
00:23:03,997 --> 00:23:08,128
- How's she doing?
- When she's depressed, she's manic.

341
00:23:08,253 --> 00:23:10,714
I think it was a good idea
to invite her to lunch.

342
00:23:10,839 --> 00:23:16,054
I hope you say it was your idea. Every
time I try to help, she gets so defensive.

343
00:23:16,180 --> 00:23:19,100
She's just embarrassed
in front of you, that's all.

344
00:23:19,267 --> 00:23:21,144
- So how are you?
- Me? I'm OK.

345
00:23:21,311 --> 00:23:22,938
- Do you miss Frederick?
- No.

346
00:23:23,105 --> 00:23:26,109
Elliot and I can't think of anyone
for you to go out with...

347
00:23:26,276 --> 00:23:30,073
How are you? Are you doing OK?
How's Frederick? I mean, Elliot?

348
00:23:30,239 --> 00:23:35,496
I guess he's fine. I don't know. He's been
kinda moody lately, the last few months.

349
00:23:35,663 --> 00:23:38,876
I don't know what's wrong.
He's distant and difficult.

350
00:23:39,001 --> 00:23:41,796
When I try to talk to him,
he says everything's fine.

351
00:23:41,921 --> 00:23:45,760
I just leap to the worst conclusion,
that he's seeing someone else or...

352
00:23:45,885 --> 00:23:48,346
Oh, no. Everyone thinks things like that.

353
00:23:48,471 --> 00:23:53,353
Well, I just came from an audition
which I did not get. So what's new?

354
00:23:53,478 --> 00:23:57,149
- They said I was too offbeat-looking.
- What the hell do they know?

355
00:23:57,274 --> 00:23:59,569
- And guess who's there, auditioning.
- April?

356
00:23:59,694 --> 00:24:02,114
- Oh, gosh.
- You got it. I was very polite.

357
00:24:02,239 --> 00:24:05,326
I maintained my poise. I said hello.

358
00:24:05,452 --> 00:24:08,998
I never trusted April.
She has eyes in the back of her head.

359
00:24:09,123 --> 00:24:13,921
She and the architect are now a very
definite item, which I still cannot believe,

360
00:24:14,046 --> 00:24:17,217
although it's put an end to the
Stanislavski Catering Company.

361
00:24:17,342 --> 00:24:20,012
I have to speak to you,
and you're gonna get impatient,

362
00:24:20,137 --> 00:24:22,348
but I have to borrow some more money.

363
00:24:22,474 --> 00:24:26,270
- Well, that's fine...
- What I've decided to do is some writing.

364
00:24:26,395 --> 00:24:30,442
I've had it with acting. These
meaningless auditions are cattle-calls.

365
00:24:30,567 --> 00:24:34,030
I can't handle another rejection.
You know, let's face it here.

366
00:24:34,155 --> 00:24:37,368
I've gotta latch onto something in my life.

367
00:24:37,493 --> 00:24:43,084
Something with a future.
I'm not 16 any more. It's just... crazy.

368
00:24:43,209 --> 00:24:47,798
But I've got an idea for a story,
more than one,

369
00:24:47,923 --> 00:24:51,636
and I just need a few months,
or a year, even.

370
00:24:51,762 --> 00:24:55,349
I've picked up a lot about
dramatic structure from acting class.

371
00:24:55,475 --> 00:25:00,898
That's good. It just seems to me
that... six months or a year,

372
00:25:01,023 --> 00:25:03,443
if you spent it more productively...

373
00:25:03,568 --> 00:25:06,823
- Like what?
- Well, I don't know. Um...

374
00:25:06,948 --> 00:25:11,036
Didn't Mom mention there was something
at the Museum of Broadcasting?

375
00:25:11,162 --> 00:25:15,793
- That's clerical.
- No, it was in the publicity department.

376
00:25:15,918 --> 00:25:19,255
- That can lead to other things.
- I knew you'd be discouraging!

377
00:25:19,422 --> 00:25:21,717
I'm not. I'm trying to be helpful.

378
00:25:21,842 --> 00:25:26,306
You don't just say one day "I'm
finished as an actress. Now I'm a writer. "

379
00:25:26,431 --> 00:25:29,519
- You mean, not at my age.
- Please, we came to have lunch.

380
00:25:29,644 --> 00:25:33,190
Yeah, OK, right. Forget it. What's to eat?

381
00:25:33,357 --> 00:25:36,736
I just want a salad.
You really think I'm a loser, don't you?

382
00:25:36,903 --> 00:25:39,281
- You're being ridiculous.
- You are. Stop it.

383
00:25:39,448 --> 00:25:41,743
- You treat me like a loser.
- How?

384
00:25:41,910 --> 00:25:44,997
You never have faith in my plans,
you undercut my enthusiasm...

385
00:25:45,122 --> 00:25:47,667
Not so, no. I think
I've been very supportive.

386
00:25:47,792 --> 00:25:50,671
I try to give you honest,
constructive advice.

387
00:25:50,796 --> 00:25:53,007
I'm always happy to help you financially.

388
00:25:53,132 --> 00:25:56,679
I've gone out of my way to introduce you
to interesting single men...

389
00:25:56,804 --> 00:25:59,474
- They're all losers.
- You're too demanding.

390
00:25:59,599 --> 00:26:02,895
I could tell what you thought of me
by the men you fixed me up with.

391
00:26:03,020 --> 00:26:05,482
- That's not true!
- I know I'm mediocre.

392
00:26:05,607 --> 00:26:09,028
Would you stop attacking Hannah?
She's going through a rough time.

393
00:26:09,153 --> 00:26:12,741
- Why are you so upset?
- You've picked on her since she came in.

394
00:26:12,866 --> 00:26:15,078
Leave her alone. I'm suffocating.

395
00:26:15,203 --> 00:26:17,915
What's the matter, Lee?
Why are you so sensitive?

396
00:26:18,040 --> 00:26:20,793
Listen. You wanna write, write.

397
00:26:20,918 --> 00:26:23,171
Let's just not talk about it any more.

398
00:26:23,296 --> 00:26:26,926
Take a year, take six months,
whatever you want.

399
00:26:27,051 --> 00:26:30,931
Who knows? Maybe you'll
be sitting with a good play.

400
00:26:31,056 --> 00:26:34,561
What's the matter with you?
You look pale. Are you OK?

401
00:26:34,686 --> 00:26:37,064
Yeah, you know, I'm just...

402
00:26:37,189 --> 00:26:42,029
I've got dizzy all of a sudden and
I have a headache. I think we need to eat.

403
00:26:57,883 --> 00:27:04,099
(Elliot) I can't seem to take action.
I'm like Hamlet, unable to kill his uncle.

404
00:27:04,224 --> 00:27:07,771
I want Lee, but I can't harm Hannah.

405
00:27:07,896 --> 00:27:10,983
And in no other area
am I a procrastinator.

406
00:27:13,361 --> 00:27:17,033
Meanwhile, Lee has no direction.
She's taking courses at Columbia.

407
00:27:17,199 --> 00:27:19,160
Butjust randomly.

408
00:27:19,285 --> 00:27:22,707
I try not to call her, but then she calls me,

409
00:27:22,832 --> 00:27:28,756
and then I call, and we try to resist
meeting, but once in a while we meet.

410
00:27:28,923 --> 00:27:32,511
Sometimes we argue because
I can't break up my marriage.

411
00:27:32,636 --> 00:27:37,601
Sometimes we wind up making love,
and we both feel terrible.

412
00:27:37,935 --> 00:27:39,937
But it's my fault.

413
00:27:41,314 --> 00:27:45,945
For all my education, accomplishments
and so-called wisdom,

414
00:27:46,112 --> 00:27:49,074
I can't fathom my own heart.

415
00:27:49,241 --> 00:27:51,077
# Krishna, Krishna

416
00:27:51,243 --> 00:27:53,622
# Hare, Hare...

417
00:27:53,747 --> 00:27:56,041
Why do you want to be a Hare Krishna?

418
00:27:56,166 --> 00:28:01,840
Well, I'm not saying I want to join, but I
know you guys believe in reincarnation.

419
00:28:01,966 --> 00:28:04,928
- What's your religion?
- I was born Jewish.

420
00:28:05,053 --> 00:28:08,558
Last winter I tried to become a Catholic,
and it didn't work for me.

421
00:28:08,683 --> 00:28:10,769
I studied and I gave it everything,

422
00:28:10,894 --> 00:28:14,398
but Catholicism for me was:
die now, pay later.

423
00:28:14,524 --> 00:28:18,153
- I couldn't get with it, and I wanted to.
- Are you afraid of dying?

424
00:28:18,278 --> 00:28:20,698
Well, yeah, naturally. Aren't you?

425
00:28:20,823 --> 00:28:24,411
Does reincarnation mean my soul
would pass to another human being,

426
00:28:24,536 --> 00:28:27,582
or would I come back as a moose
or an aardvark or something?

427
00:28:27,707 --> 00:28:31,963
Take our literature,
read it over and think about it.

428
00:28:32,088 --> 00:28:36,218
- OK. Thank you very much.
- You're welcome. Hare Krishna.

429
00:28:39,139 --> 00:28:42,017
Who are you kidding?
You're gonna be a Krishna?

430
00:28:42,143 --> 00:28:46,106
You're gonna shave your head and put on
robes and dance around at airports?

431
00:28:46,231 --> 00:28:48,860
You'll look like Jerry Lewis.

432
00:28:48,985 --> 00:28:51,029
God, I'm so depressed.

433
00:29:01,251 --> 00:29:04,129
(Lee) The nights are really getting cooler.

434
00:29:04,254 --> 00:29:08,135
Summer went so quickly. Soon it'll be fall.

435
00:29:10,179 --> 00:29:12,932
My literature professor really likes me.

436
00:29:13,058 --> 00:29:16,103
It was fun being out with him last night.

437
00:29:16,228 --> 00:29:20,609
Funny, I feel like I'm betraying Elliot,
but that's ridiculous.

438
00:29:20,734 --> 00:29:23,988
Why shouldn't I see Doug?
Elliot's not free.

439
00:29:25,073 --> 00:29:27,117
Just go one step at a time.

440
00:29:28,202 --> 00:29:31,164
Let's see what the next few months bring.

441
00:29:31,957 --> 00:29:34,085
Hannah? Hi!

442
00:29:34,210 --> 00:29:39,008
Listen, you'll be happy to know that your
money has not gone completely to waste.

443
00:29:39,175 --> 00:29:43,138
No, I have an actual first rough draft
of something I wrote.

444
00:29:43,305 --> 00:29:45,349
Yeah, yeah.

445
00:29:45,516 --> 00:29:48,687
I showed it to Lee and
she gave me some good pointers.

446
00:29:48,812 --> 00:29:52,567
Listen, I'm pretty near where you live.
Could I just drop it off?

447
00:29:52,734 --> 00:29:57,407
When you have some time, read it,
and we'll talk at Thanksgiving.

448
00:29:57,573 --> 00:30:00,661
OK? All right. Oh, wait, listen.

449
00:30:01,537 --> 00:30:06,961
I think Lee met an interesting guy
at Columbia. He sounds really nice.

450
00:30:08,045 --> 00:30:12,676
Yeah, OK, all right. Well,
we'll talk at Thanksgiving. Bye-bye.

451
00:30:14,136 --> 00:30:17,474
Now, here's a song that Norma sang

